Github website

Goals of This Project:

  1. Determine which performance metrics are determinants of winning races.

    • I will utilize a regression model using historical data on each circuit to predict how a particular driver will do given their success in a given season. Essentially, I will be utilzing historical data of all drivers at a particular race, to predict how a similar driver may do at the same particular race

  2. Determine the role that constructors play in pit stops, qualifiers, and ultimately winning races. Utilize historical data, to predict which constructor will win based on their performance in a given season

    • I will utilize another regression model using historical data on each of the constructors. I will analyze how the constructors have performed at similar circuits over time and extrapolate said analysis to build a prediciton model that will estimate how the constructors will do based on the upcoming race schedule.

Data Sets Overview:

  1. circuits.csv : This dataset gives an overview of the different circuits within Formula One and their geographical information. A circuit is the track where a Formula One race occurs

  2. constructor_results.csv : This dataset summarizes how each constructor did at each race and how many points they received.

  3. constructor_standings.csv : This dataset highlights how each constructor did at specific races as well as the points their team received for said standings

  4. constructors.csv : This dataset gives information on the different constructors within Formula One, their specific ID, and nationality. A constructor in Formula One is a company that designs and builds the race cars. Each team has a unique constructor

  5. driver_standings.csv : This dataset illustrates the outcomes of each race. It shows how each driver did at specific races and how many points were awarded

  6. drivers.csv : This dataset gives detailed information on all Formula One drivers for the past 70+ years. Within this dataset, there is information on nationality as well as age.

  7. lap_times.csv : This dataset details each driver and how they performed each lap of every race. Each row signifies how a specific driver performed for each lap. We are given position after completing the lap as well as the time of lap

  8. pit_stops.csv : This dataset provides information about all pitstops within the races. The pitstop dataset provides detailed information on stop length, what lap the stop occurred, and which driver was stopping.

  9. qualifying.csv : To determine grid placement on race day, drivers compete in qualifying rounds on Saturday. This dataset details how each driver did at qualifiers, the overall time for each lap, and the placement earned for Sunday's race

  10. races.csv : This dataset gives specific IDs to each race within Formula One between 1950-2022. The dataset has information on the circuit, what date the race was on, and even what time the race began

  11. results.csv : This dataset summarizes pertinent information regarding the results of each Formula One race. Within the dataset, we can see where each driver started, where they finished and their fastest lap time

  12. seasons.csv : This dataset provides a quick Wikipedia link for pertinent information on each Formula One Season.

  13. sprint_results.csv : Sprint races are new to Formula One. They are not offered at every race but only typically at 'big' races. Only 1/3 the time of a normal race, the drivers compete in a 'mock race' to earn more points for their team and learn the track. This dataset captures important timing and placing metrics for the recent sprint races.

  14. status.csv : This is a foreign key table that provides text explanations for the different race statuses

Data Set Citations

  1. I found all of these datasets on Kaggle. The user who posted these datasets cleaned the data and compiled each table from http://ergast.com/mrd/

qualifying dataframe¶

How do qualifying rounds work in Formula One?

There are three qualifying rounds for each race weekend in Formula One. These rounds take place typically over two days prior to the race on Sunday. In the first round, all twenty Formula One drivers participate. The driver's race one lap individually and attempt to recieve the fastest time. Those in the top fifteen will move on to the second round of qualifiers. Those with the bottom five times, will start race day in the last five positions on the grid. In the second round of qualifiers, drivers drive one lap, once again aiming for the faastest time. Those with the fastest ten times will move on to the third round of qualifiers. Those who had the bottom five race times in Q2 will be placed in spots 10-15 on the grid for Sunday's race. The final qualifying round determines the order of the drivers who will be in positions 1-10 on race day.

How should this information shape our data?

Since not all drivers will participate in all three rounds of qualifying, I am going to create dummy variables that will indicate (based on their success in qualifiers) whether a driver will race in the top ten, middle five, or bottom five.

qualifying = qualifying.drop(columns = ["number"])
qualifying = qualifying.replace('\\N','0')
qualifying['top_ten'] = np.where(qualifying['q3'] != '0' , 1, 0)
qualifying['middle'] = np.where((qualifying['q3'] == '0') & (qualifying['q2'] >'0'), 1, 0)
qualifying['bottom_five'] = np.where((qualifying['q3']=='0') & (qualifying['q2']=='0'), 1, 0)
qualifying = qualifying.rename(columns= {"position" : "starting_position"})

working towards predictive model one¶

As mentioned in the project goals, I would like to create a predictive model where finishing position is the dependent variable of which we are predicting for. I will groupby circuitID and driverID to determine average lap speed, the fastest lap speed and the fastest lap time given a particular driver at a particular circuit. Utilizing these three metrics, I will then take the historical data and predict how a particular driver with X average lap speed, Y fastest lap speed, and Z fastest lap time will perform at a particular circuit.

Steps to build this regression model

  1. Merge the results dataframe with the races dataframe to obtain information on which circuit was driven at a particular race.

    Once there is information on circuits, sort by the circuitID and driverID and calculate the average lap time, fastest lap time, and fastest lap speed for each driver at a particulat circuit. Note, this will best be displayed in a pivot table

  2. Limit the results dataframe to only contain information on the drivers, their starting and ending position, the amount of laps in the race, the time of their race in milliseconds, information on their fastest lap and circuit identification.
  3. Merge the new results data frame with the other three dataframes mentioned.
    • First we will merge the combined laps dataframe with qualifying.
    • We will complete an inner merge on race and driver IDs to ensure that we only keep information that is for a specific driver at a specific race.
    • Secondly, we will merge this new dataset with information we downselected from the results dataframe
    • This will also be an inner merge on driver and race ID as we are trying to keep our observations limited to specific drivers at specific circuits.
  4. Utilizing our newly created dataframe, we will calculate the correlation between important quantitative variables and begin to understand what regressors should be utilized in predicting finishing position.
  5. Finally, we will build our regression model. In order to fairly assess the data, we will utilize data only from 2000 to 2022. After splitting our data, we will use fivefold cross validation to build the best predictive model for where a driver will finish given how similar drivers have competed at the same circuit.

working through the second predictive model¶

As mentioned in the project goals, I want to determine the role that the constructor, rather than the driver, plays in how races turn out. Within a Formula 1 season, there are two important competitions happening at any given time. These two competitions are the Driver's world championship and the constructors world champtionship. Where my previous model predicted how a driver may do at a given race, I want to build my second model to predict how a constructor will do in a given season based on the lineup of races. I will utilize similar data as before, however, know I will also include information based on the constructors and I will group driverIDs based on who they are racing for within a given season

exceess information still to be worked through¶

The Constructor Datasets

  • I want to use this dataset to help determine if the driver or the engine is more integral to winning the race
  • Performing somewhat of a difference-in-differences analysis, I can compare how different drivers who switch teams perform overtime. Does the constructor vastly improve their performance or does other factors?

Regression Discontinuity¶

observing the effect a team has on drivers

Scaping information from the internet, specific to the ten current racing teams within the last decade¶

For any given Formula One season, there are ten constructors/ teams. The current lineup includes Red Bull Racing, Mercedes, Ferrari, Mclaren, AlphaTauri,Alpine F1 Team, Alfa Romeo, Haas F1 team, Aston Martin & Williams. I have limited my regression discontinuity to these teams because Formula One is both highly transient (in the past 72 years, there have been over 171 constructors) and it is constantly developing (it would be unwise to build a model using information from Ferrari cars 50 years ago to predict how Ferrari will do next year). In addition to limiting the constructors, I have also limited teams that have a large historical footprint in Formula One to only include data from 2010 onwards

# Alfa Romeo 
# Please note Alfa Romeo has raced in 1950-1951, 1979-1985, and 2019-2022 but for this project I will only include the third set of dates
url = 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfa_Romeo_in_Formula_One'
headers = {'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_10_1) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/39.0.2171.95 Safari/537.36'}
r = requests.get(url, headers=headers)
# importing the ability to use beautiful soup 
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
soup = BeautifulSoup( r.content )

alfa_drivers = []
for t in soup.findAll("table"):
  df_t = pd.read_html(str(t))
  alfa_drivers.append(df_t[0])

alfa_drivers[2] = alfa_drivers[2][['Year', 'Drivers']]
alfa_drivers[2] = alfa_drivers[2].dropna()
alfa_drivers[2].drop([2], axis =0, inplace =True)
alfa_drivers[2].drop([10], axis =0, inplace =True)
alfa_drivers[2].drop([15], axis =0, inplace =True)
alfa_drivers[2].drop(alfa_drivers[2].loc[0:9].index, axis =0, inplace =True)

alfa_drivers[2] = alfa_drivers[2].join(alfa_drivers[2]['Drivers'].str.split( expand =True).rename(
    columns = {0: 'First1', 1: 'Last1', 2:'First2', 3:'Last2', 4:'First3', 5:'Last3'}))

alfa_drivers[2]['Driver1'] = alfa_drivers[2]['First1']  + ' ' + alfa_drivers[2]['Last1'] 
alfa_drivers[2]['Driver2'] = alfa_drivers[2]['First2']  + ' ' + alfa_drivers[2]['Last2'] 
alfa_drivers[2]['Driver3'] = alfa_drivers[2]['First3']  + ' ' + alfa_drivers[2]['Last3'] 

alfa_drivers[2] = alfa_drivers[2][['Year', 'Driver1', 'Driver2', 'Driver3']]

alfa_drivers[2] = pd.melt(alfa_drivers[2], id_vars=['Year'])
alfa_drivers[2] = alfa_drivers[2].dropna()

alfa_drivers[2]['Constructor'] = 'Alfa Romeo'
alfa_drivers[2]= alfa_drivers[2].drop(columns= ['variable'])
alfa_drivers[2] = alfa_drivers[2].rename(columns={"value": "Driver"})
alfa_drivers[2]['constructorId'] = '51'

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb

            which will convert mynotebook.ipynb to the default format (probably HTML).

            You can specify the export format with `--to`.
            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic' and 'full'. You
            can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template basic mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of 
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
